Pretty concise solution with plain Java 8 using [`java.util.stream`](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/package-summary.html):

    public static &lt;T&gt; ArrayList&lt;T&gt; toArrayList(final Iterator&lt;T&gt; iterator) {
        return StreamSupport
            .stream(
                Spliterators
                    .spliteratorUnknownSize(iterator, Spliterator.ORDERED), false)
            .collect(
                    Collectors.toCollection(ArrayList::new)
        );
    }

In Java 8, you can use the new `forEachRemaining` method that&#39;s been added to the `Iterator` interface:

    List&lt;Element&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    iterator.forEachRemaining(list::add);

Note there is a difference between [`Iterable`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/Iterable.html) and [`Iterator`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Iterator.html).

If you have an **`Iterable`**, then with Java 8 you can use this solution:

    Iterable&lt;Element&gt; iterable = createIterable();
    List&lt;Element&gt; array = StreamSupport
        .stream(iterable.spliterator(), false)
        .collect(Collectors.toList());

As I know `Collectors.toList()` creates `ArrayList` instance.

Actually in my opinion, it also looks good in one line.  
For example if you need to return `List&lt;Element&gt;` from some method:

    return StreamSupport.stream(iter.spliterator(), false).collect(Collectors.toList());

Try [`StickyList`](http://static.javadoc.io/org.cactoos/cactoos/0.20.2/org/cactoos/list/StickyList.html) from [Cactoos](http://www.cactoos.org):

    List&lt;String&gt; list = new StickyList&lt;&gt;(iterable);

Disclaimer: I&#39;m one of the developers.

I just want to point out a seemingly obvious solution that **will NOT** work:

&lt;pre&gt;
&lt;s&gt;List&lt;Element&gt; list = Stream.generate(iterator::next)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());&lt;/s&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;

That&#39;s because [`Stream#generate(Supplier&lt;T&gt;)`](//docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Stream.html#generate-java.util.function.Supplier-) can create only infinite streams, it doesn&#39;t expect its argument to throw [`NoSuchElementException`](//docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/NoSuchElementException.html) (that&#39;s what [`Iterator#next()`](//docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Iterator.html#next--) will do in the end).

[The xehpuk&#39;s answer](//stackoverflow.com/a/23997880) should be used instead if the Iterator→Stream→List way is your choice.

**Without external dependency**, here&#39;s a one-liner using Streams and java 16 toList().

Given an `Iterator&lt;?&gt; iterator`:

    List&lt;?&gt; list = StreamSupport.stream(Spliterators.spliteratorUnknownSize(iterator, 0), false).toList();

